WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:01.800
Well, good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:01.800 --> 00:00:05.000
I'm Joseph Rickert from RStudio.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.160
And I am a director of the R Consortium.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:11.560
And I'm here with David Smith, my fellow director

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:16.160
from Microsoft, who's also a director of the R Consortium.

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:18.700
And what we'd like to do is give you

00:00:18.700 --> 00:00:24.360
some idea about the R Consortium and why we exist.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:29.799
So first off, in simplest terms, the R Consortium

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:33.480
is a group of business enterprises

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:37.080
and philanthropic enterprises who

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:40.480
have an interest in ensuring that the R

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:46.959
language and the R community thrive for the long term.

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:53.439
So the consortium is the vehicle for the participation

00:00:53.439 --> 00:00:56.240
of businesses in the R community.

00:00:56.240 --> 00:00:59.520
The way I think about it is that to have a community

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:02.520
like the R community, there are three necessary conditions.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:04.680
You have to have people who self-identify

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:11.120
as part of the community, people who interact frequently,

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:13.800
and there has to be a way for people

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:16.040
to contribute to the community.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:21.000
So the R Consortium is a way for businesses

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.839
to contribute to the community.

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:29.639
And right now, what we have here is a list of the members.

00:01:29.639 --> 00:01:33.080
And what you see are the founding members, RStudio

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:34.680
and Microsoft.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:38.800
And then on the end there, you see the addition this year

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:40.959
of the Moore Foundation, the Gordon and Betty Moore

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:44.720
Foundation, which I believe is a significant development

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:49.559
because it shows that a well-established

00:01:49.559 --> 00:01:54.000
philanthropic grant-giving organization who's

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.519
interested in promoting science and technology in the United

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:04.879
States has recognized that R is a key contributor

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:08.399
and enabler for the scientific community.

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:12.600
And on the bottom here, you see some organizations

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:19.199
that are not directly making their business

00:02:19.199 --> 00:02:22.600
around the R language, like Google, for instance.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:26.199
Or you have here, this little mountain there

00:02:26.199 --> 00:02:30.600
is Ketchum Trading, which is a hedge fund in Chicago.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:32.880
These are smaller organizations who

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:35.880
recognize that they have a significant dependence

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.960
on the R language, and they want to become

00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:40.479
members of the community.

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:46.720
So here we have a way for businesses

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:49.279
and other organizations to become a member.

00:02:49.279 --> 00:02:51.279
And we see ourselves as the link here.

00:02:51.279 --> 00:02:54.679
So the possibilities are that we could

00:02:54.679 --> 00:02:59.440
be the place that bind the community, which

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:02.679
is at the people level, industry, which

00:03:02.679 --> 00:03:07.000
is a category above, collections of people, the R Foundation,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.600
which is, of course, an organization made up

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:12.520
of people who are also individuals.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:16.440
So this is how we solve the, we see ourselves

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:19.279
as a link.

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:25.839
Now, there are two major ways that we provide energy

00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:27.039
and money.

00:03:27.039 --> 00:03:30.160
So the energy part is exemplified

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:32.479
by this slide here.

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:35.559
We have the concept of working groups.

00:03:35.559 --> 00:03:38.399
And if you've ever worked in a standards organization,

00:03:38.399 --> 00:03:43.440
like the IEEE or other trade organizations,

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.080
you can see that there's lots of opinions

00:03:46.119 --> 00:03:49.000
about how things should be done, right?

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.800
And it's very important before you do anything

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:56.119
to try to achieve consensus, perhaps

00:03:56.119 --> 00:03:59.559
get some funding to work out initial prototypes.

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:03.639
And that's what the R Consortium Working Group is for.

00:04:03.639 --> 00:04:07.479
So you see we have some already underway.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:13.720
And this graphic on the right here

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:17.079
is, that's the reference architecture

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:19.160
for the Distributed Computing Working Group.

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:21.920
Now, what they're working on is to try to figure out

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:25.920
if there is a single interface layer that, say,

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:30.359
could be built that would be the proper way for people

00:04:30.359 --> 00:04:34.320
to write to if they were interested in using

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:37.079
different distributed computing back end.

00:04:37.079 --> 00:04:40.679
So it's not an obvious solution.

00:04:40.679 --> 00:04:42.239
And they're working at it.

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:47.480
We see ourselves as a catalyst.

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:50.119
We're delightful to see the success

00:04:50.119 --> 00:04:54.200
that Our Ladies is having.

00:04:54.200 --> 00:05:00.920
We funded Our Ladies during the last round last year,

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:02.320
just a small amount of money.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:06.200
And we certainly can't take any kind of credit for the success.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:09.519
But this is a slide that they presented to us

00:05:09.519 --> 00:05:12.559
when we went through the exercise of seeing

00:05:12.559 --> 00:05:15.040
how our investments were turning out.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:19.040
And we're just delighted to see how much progress they've

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:21.079
made and continue to make.

00:05:21.079 --> 00:05:23.959
And it's an example of sometimes you

00:05:23.959 --> 00:05:26.040
have something that's working at one level,

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:28.720
and then maybe a little bit of money or attention.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:31.359
In this case, I think maybe just attention.

00:05:31.359 --> 00:05:32.720
And it works wonders.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:37.799
A place where people can come together.

00:05:37.839 --> 00:05:45.920
So we mostly fund what we call infrastructure projects.

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:48.760
But we have an extended idea of infrastructure.

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:52.760
And getting people, small conferences and ways

00:05:52.760 --> 00:05:55.760
for people to meet are also part of our mission.

00:05:59.279 --> 00:06:02.359
We're interested really in complicated projects.

00:06:02.359 --> 00:06:06.160
So when we go out for a call for papers, what we like to see

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:09.600
are proposals from groups or individuals

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.079
or groups of individuals who were

00:06:12.079 --> 00:06:15.000
willing to undertake something that

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.200
will benefit a large portion of the art community

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:22.679
and something big enough that it needs organizational help.

00:06:26.799 --> 00:06:28.799
And then we're the resource for the heavy lifting.

00:06:28.799 --> 00:06:31.559
So the R-Hub project, which many of you

00:06:31.559 --> 00:06:35.119
have probably seen a tutorial on yesterday,

00:06:35.119 --> 00:06:37.320
was some kind of motivating project

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:39.200
for the art consortium.

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:42.000
What happens when you need to begin

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.160
to put together the infrastructure for a modern day

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:48.119
build system that will last through the 21st century?

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:56.079
This is what it takes to be on the consortium.

00:06:56.079 --> 00:07:01.519
And it shows the commitment that these companies have made.

00:07:01.519 --> 00:07:07.320
So to be a platinum member, that's $100,000 dues per year.

00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:12.160
A gold member, which is underneath that, is $50,000.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:17.079
And the silver member is $25,000 for organizations

00:07:17.079 --> 00:07:19.679
that are over 100 people.

00:07:19.679 --> 00:07:21.760
What I'd like to see is the growth

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:26.440
in the consortium with lots of smaller members contributing.

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:30.839
Because we're all stronger when people become involved.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:33.079
There's two major committees.

00:07:33.079 --> 00:07:36.239
You can see there's the board of directors that we're on.

00:07:36.239 --> 00:07:39.559
And that's involved with strategic decisions

00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:42.679
and how much money we have to spend.

00:07:42.679 --> 00:07:44.920
The infrastructure steering committee

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:48.079
is the group that actually decides

00:07:48.079 --> 00:07:49.760
what projects get funded.

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:54.959
And they issue the call for papers and what have you.

00:07:54.959 --> 00:08:03.359
And this is a list of the active projects that are going now.

00:08:03.359 --> 00:08:04.760
You see, I'm up there on the board

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:08.320
because I run our user group support program.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:12.000
So if you're organizing a user group,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.799
there is some money to be had depending

00:08:14.799 --> 00:08:16.200
on the size of the group.

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:21.600
So please look at our consortium web page and write to us

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:24.320
and tell us about your group.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:28.640
And you see the grants range from small grants,

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:32.760
you know, in the $5,000 range to the R-Hub

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.520
is a significant project.

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:39.400
So we're prepared to undertake real infrastructure.

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:43.440
But our mission is to spread the money around.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:46.679
This is money that comes to us in dues.

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:50.960
Right now, we're up to getting close to having handed out

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:52.880
half a million dollars.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:54.039
And we're pretty efficient.

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:59.479
I think the last I looked, our efficiency ratio is about 70%.

00:08:59.479 --> 00:09:02.080
And we'd like to even do better than that.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:06.320
So the money comes in from the companies.

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:07.919
They have an interest in fostering

00:09:07.919 --> 00:09:10.719
the community, the foundation, and the language.

00:09:10.719 --> 00:09:13.080
And we're trying to hand it back intelligently

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:16.000
to people who have real contributions to make.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.159
So, David.

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:19.840
Thank you, Jerry.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:23.440
I wanted to jump in at this point.

00:09:23.479 --> 00:09:25.880
If I turn it that way, it'll go forwards.

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:27.200
I wanted to jump at this point

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:29.679
and just give a little perspective

00:09:29.679 --> 00:09:32.960
from the point of view of Microsoft.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:37.960
And why did Microsoft become a member of the R Consortium?

00:09:38.479 --> 00:09:40.640
And it has to do with what I said

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:42.599
if you saw my talk this morning,

00:09:42.599 --> 00:09:46.679
is that the value of software, including R,

00:09:46.679 --> 00:09:49.159
lies not just in its technical capability,

00:09:49.159 --> 00:09:52.159
but also in the ecosystem that forms around it.

00:09:52.159 --> 00:09:56.960
And Microsoft has a lot of interest

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:00.559
in R having a thriving ecosystem around it.

00:10:00.559 --> 00:10:02.679
You know, Microsoft is a fine and noble company,

00:10:02.679 --> 00:10:05.599
but it doesn't do things out of the goodness of its heart,

00:10:05.599 --> 00:10:07.119
should it have one.

00:10:07.119 --> 00:10:12.119
Microsoft is very selfishly investing in the R Consortium

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:16.840
to foster the growth and success of the R community.

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:18.559
In its technical capabilities,

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:20.840
to give you one very specific example,

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:23.119
Microsoft has a very vested interest

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:25.960
in R being able to access databases very well.

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:27.359
And there is a DBI project

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:29.359
that was funded by the R Consortium

00:10:29.359 --> 00:10:32.599
in order to unify the way that R connects with databases,

00:10:32.599 --> 00:10:35.200
which is very much in Microsoft's interests.

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:37.640
It's also important from a talent perspective.

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:40.719
Both we at Microsoft and our customers and partners

00:10:40.719 --> 00:10:44.640
that are working with R need to be able to hire people.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.440
And by investing in the R Consortium

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:47.599
and being public about that,

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:50.559
that helps us with our recruitment goals.

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:52.599
Also around the vendor network,

00:10:52.599 --> 00:10:53.760
you know, being able to work

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:56.280
with the other vendors in the space,

00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:59.760
you know, like RStudio, like TIBCO, like everybody else,

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:02.520
and have just unified discussions

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:05.840
about how R is working in the commercial environment

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:07.840
is very, very important to us at Microsoft.

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:09.080
So from our perspective,

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:13.559
we get very good value out of that $100,000 a year

00:11:13.559 --> 00:11:15.200
that we invest in the R Consortium,

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:18.440
which in turn gets invested into the broader ecosystem

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:19.799
as Joe just described.

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:23.599
Just to give some summaries about the R Consortium

00:11:23.599 --> 00:11:26.200
since it's been running for a couple of years now,

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:29.039
we currently do have 13 members,

00:11:29.039 --> 00:11:31.760
four of which are that top level platinum member,

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:34.320
actually, rather than gold as listed there.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:36.599
We would love to have more.

00:11:36.599 --> 00:11:39.479
So if you are working at an organization

00:11:39.479 --> 00:11:40.919
which is doing a lot with R,

00:11:40.919 --> 00:11:43.479
please do talk to your leadership

00:11:43.479 --> 00:11:45.919
about potentially becoming a member of the R Consortium,

00:11:45.919 --> 00:11:48.359
and in turn, contributing to the ecosystem

00:11:48.359 --> 00:11:50.080
in the ways that I just described.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.679
But the thing that I think I'm most personally proud of

00:11:53.679 --> 00:11:55.039
as a founding member,

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:57.039
and I'm sure the other members are as well,

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:00.119
is the projects that the members of the community

00:12:00.119 --> 00:12:02.559
have been able to undertake

00:12:02.559 --> 00:12:04.880
through the R Consortium sponsorship,

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:08.520
and not just the projects, but also the working groups

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:11.359
and the social organizations that Joe mentioned as well.

00:12:12.919 --> 00:12:16.119
Another thing that I think is really, really important

00:12:16.119 --> 00:12:18.520
that the R Consortium has achieved

00:12:18.559 --> 00:12:22.320
is to open up a conduit between the vendor community

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:23.840
that is working with Microsoft

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:26.799
and directly with the leadership of the R Foundation.

00:12:26.799 --> 00:12:30.679
One of the ways the governance structure

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:32.719
of the R Consortium is designed

00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:34.719
is that the R Foundation

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:38.400
automatically has a seat on the board,

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:39.640
participates in the board meetings,

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:41.719
participates in the discussions,

00:12:41.719 --> 00:12:44.440
and that has really improved the communication

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:47.080
back and forth between the vendor community

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:48.520
and the R core group.

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:51.880
Right now, Robert Gentleman is representing the R Foundation

00:12:51.880 --> 00:12:53.719
on the board of the R Consortium.

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:58.719
And in general, it's just providing a secure,

00:12:58.719 --> 00:13:02.239
long-term foundation for R as a whole,

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:06.760
R as an ecosystem from these vested interests

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:08.799
of the vendors that are working around R.

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:12.559
So what's coming up?

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:16.400
One of the projects that the R Consortium

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:18.760
is investing in right now and undertaking

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:21.960
is a general survey of the R community.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:24.400
This is essentially an academic survey.

00:13:24.400 --> 00:13:25.320
It's been designed.

00:13:25.320 --> 00:13:26.320
We spent a working group,

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:28.559
spent about three months designing this survey.

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:30.400
It's only recently been launched,

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:32.200
but we would love to hear from you

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:34.679
and any member of the R community broadly

00:13:34.679 --> 00:13:38.000
that might be watching online or anybody who is using R

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.719
to provide information about what you think

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:45.719
about the past, present, and future of the R project.

00:13:46.599 --> 00:13:48.200
There'll be a link at the end of the presentation,

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:51.880
but please do visit the R Consortium blog

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:54.039
or the R Consortium Twitter handle

00:13:54.039 --> 00:13:56.119
to see a link to that survey.

00:13:56.119 --> 00:13:57.559
There are also a number of new projects

00:13:57.559 --> 00:14:00.280
that have already been funded and are kicking off soon.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:02.320
If you'd like to read about those new projects,

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:05.080
that's on the R Consortium blog at the link there.

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:07.799
And if you have been inspired by projects

00:14:07.799 --> 00:14:11.440
that you and some colleagues might wish to undertake,

00:14:11.440 --> 00:14:13.080
there will be a new round of proposals

00:14:13.080 --> 00:14:15.080
being announced later on this year

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:16.359
where you can make an application

00:14:16.359 --> 00:14:19.400
and apply for funding in the same way we saw.

00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:21.760
So just in general, to wrap up,

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:25.559
the R Consortium is there to promote the growth

00:14:25.559 --> 00:14:30.200
and development of R as a leading platform for data science,

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:33.039
to provide support directly to the R Foundation

00:14:33.039 --> 00:14:35.679
through that connection I mentioned a moment ago,

00:14:35.679 --> 00:14:38.400
to fund projects that are supporting the R project

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:39.840
and the R community,

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:42.359
and foster the growth of that R community.

00:14:42.359 --> 00:14:44.320
And then from the point of view of the vendors,

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:48.080
to help enable the use of R in commercial environments

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:50.159
and foster collaboration between those companies

00:14:50.159 --> 00:14:52.599
that are using R in that commercial sector.

00:14:53.760 --> 00:14:56.679
So, as I mentioned earlier on,

00:14:56.679 --> 00:14:59.520
help us to help you be part of that community.

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:01.679
Please talk to your company

00:15:01.679 --> 00:15:03.719
about potentially becoming a member.

00:15:03.719 --> 00:15:06.919
Think about projects and submit them to the R Consortium

00:15:06.919 --> 00:15:08.919
when the new round comes out shortly.

00:15:08.919 --> 00:15:10.320
Have a look at the existing projects

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:11.280
that are currently underway,

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:14.119
and if you'd like to chip in and help with those, please do.

00:15:14.919 --> 00:15:17.919
And follow us and spread the word on Twitter and at the blog.

00:15:17.919 --> 00:15:19.280
Thank you very much.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:21.280
APPLAUSE

